@startuml design-patterns
title "Infraware Terminal - Design Patterns Reference"

!define ACCENTCOLOR #4A90E2
!define PATTERNCOLOR #E8F4F8
!define CHAINSUPPORT #FFF4E6
!define STRATEGYCOLOR #F0E6FF
!define BUILDERCOLOR #E8F8E8
!define SRPCOLOR #FFE8F0

skinparam style strictuml
skinparam backgroundColor #FFFFFF
skinparam NoteBackgroundColor #FFFACD
skinparam NoteBorderColor #FFD700
skinparam ClassBackgroundColor #F5F5F5
skinparam ClassBorderColor ACCENTCOLOR

' 1. Chain of Responsibility Pattern
package "1. Chain of Responsibility" {
    note as COR_OVERVIEW
        **Pattern**: Chain of Responsibility
        **Purpose**: Process input through series of handlers
        **Benefits**: Flexible handler ordering, easy to add/remove handlers
        **Implementation**: Each handler returns None if can't handle
    end note

    class ClassifierChain #PATTERNCOLOR {
        - handlers: Vec<Box<dyn InputHandler>>
        --
        + process(input: &str): Option<InputType>
    }

    interface InputHandler #PATTERNCOLOR <<trait>> {
        + handle(input: &str): Option<InputType>
    }

    class InputHandlerImpl_1 #CHAINSUPPORT {
        Handler 1: EmptyInputHandler
        --
        Checks for empty/whitespace input
    }

    class InputHandlerImpl_2 #CHAINSUPPORT {
        Handler 2: HistoryExpansionHandler
        --
        Expands !!,  !$, !^, !*
    }

    class InputHandlerImpl_3 #CHAINSUPPORT {
        Handler 3-9: Other handlers
        --
        Each passes to next if unable to handle
    }

    class ChainTerminator #CHAINSUPPORT {
        Handler 9: DefaultHandler
        --
        Fallback: Always matches (guarantees result)
    }

    ClassifierChain *-- InputHandler
    InputHandler <|-- InputHandlerImpl_1
    InputHandler <|-- InputHandlerImpl_2
    InputHandler <|-- InputHandlerImpl_3
    InputHandler <|-- ChainTerminator

    note right of ClassifierChain
        **SCAN Algorithm Uses Chain of Responsibility**:

        Handler Chain (Order Critical):
        1. EmptyInputHandler - O(1)
        2. HistoryExpansionHandler - O(n)
        3. ShellBuiltinHandler - O(1)
        4. PathCommandHandler - O(10)
        5. KnownCommandHandler - O(log n) cache
        6. CommandSyntaxHandler - O(n) regex
        7. TypoDetectionHandler - O(n*m) Levenshtein
        8. NaturalLanguageHandler - O(n) regex
        9. DefaultHandler - O(1)

        **Performance Optimization**: Fast paths first
        - 70% of inputs hit handler 5 (KnownCommands)
        - Average time: <100μs
        - 99% of lookup is cache hits
    end note
}

' 2. Strategy Pattern
package "2. Strategy Pattern" {
    note as STRATEGY_OVERVIEW
        **Pattern**: Strategy
        **Purpose**: Select algorithm at runtime based on context
        **Benefits**: Easy to add new strategies, no modification to existing code
        **Implementation**: Interface with multiple implementations
    end note

    interface PackageManager #STRATEGYCOLOR <<trait>> {
        + name(): &str
        + is_available(): bool
        + install(package: &str): Result<()>
        + priority(): u8
    }

    class AptStrategy #STRATEGYCOLOR {
        PackageManager for apt-get
        Platform: Debian/Ubuntu
        Priority: MEDIUM (80)
    }

    class BrewStrategy #STRATEGYCOLOR {
        PackageManager for brew
        Platform: macOS
        Priority: VERY_HIGH (90)
    }

    class WingetStrategy #STRATEGYCOLOR {
        PackageManager for winget
        Platform: Windows
        Priority: HIGH (85)
    }

    class OtherStrategies #STRATEGYCOLOR {
        Yum, Dnf, Pacman
        Choco
    }

    class PackageInstaller {
        - managers: Vec<Arc<dyn PackageManager>>
        --
        + detect_package_manager(): Option<Arc<dyn PM>>
        + install(package: &str): Result<()>
    }

    PackageManager <|-- AptStrategy
    PackageManager <|-- BrewStrategy
    PackageManager <|-- WingetStrategy
    PackageManager <|-- OtherStrategies

    PackageInstaller --> PackageManager

    note right of PackageInstaller
        **Strategy Selection Algorithm**:
        1. Check all managers for availability
        2. Sort by priority (highest first)
        3. Use first available
        4. Fallback: error if none available

        **Cross-Platform Support**:
        - macOS: Brew highest priority
        - Linux: Dnf/Apt/Yum/Pacman available
        - Windows: Winget > Choco

        **Extensibility**: Add new manager:
        1. Implement PackageManager trait
        2. Add to PackageInstaller::detect()
        3. No changes to existing managers
    end note
}

' 3. Builder Pattern
package "3. Builder Pattern" {
    note as BUILDER_OVERVIEW
        **Pattern**: Builder
        **Purpose**: Flexible, testable object construction
        **Benefits**: Optional dependencies, easy to test with mocks
        **Implementation**: Builder struct with with_*() methods
    end note

    class InfrawareTerminalBuilder #BUILDERCOLOR {
        - ui: Option<TerminalUI>
        - state: Option<TerminalState>
        - classifier: Option<InputClassifier>
        - llm_client: Option<Arc<dyn LLMClientTrait>>
        - renderer: Option<ResponseRenderer>
        --
        + with_ui(ui: TerminalUI): Self
        + with_state(state: TerminalState): Self
        + with_classifier(classifier: InputClassifier): Self
        + with_llm_client(client: Arc<dyn LLMClientTrait>): Self
        + with_renderer(renderer: ResponseRenderer): Self
        + build(): Result<InfrawareTerminal>
    }

    class InfrawareTerminal {
        Built from builder
    }

    InfrawareTerminalBuilder ..> InfrawareTerminal : builds

    note right of InfrawareTerminalBuilder
        **Builder Usage Examples**:

        **Production**:
        ```rust
        let terminal = InfrawareTerminal::builder()
            .with_llm_client(Arc::new(HttpLLMClient::new(url)))
            .build()?;
        ```

        **Testing with Mock**:
        ```rust
        let terminal = InfrawareTerminal::builder()
            .with_llm_client(Arc::new(MockLLMClient::new()))
            .with_state(custom_state)
            .build()?;
        ```

        **Benefits**:
        - Dependency injection for testability
        - Sensible defaults for missing components
        - Clear intent in construction code
        - Easy to add new optional components
    end note
}

' 4. Single Responsibility Principle
package "4. Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)" {
    note as SRP_OVERVIEW
        **Pattern**: Single Responsibility Principle
        **Purpose**: Each component has one reason to change
        **Benefits**: Easier testing, maintenance, reusability
        **Implementation**: Separate concerns into focused classes
    end note

    class OutputBuffer #SRPCOLOR {
        Responsibility:
        Manage scrollable output display
        --
        + add_line(line: String)
        + scroll_up()
        + scroll_down()
    }

    class InputBuffer #SRPCOLOR {
        Responsibility:
        Manage text input + cursor
        --
        + insert_char(c: char)
        + move_cursor_left()
        + delete_char()
    }

    class CommandHistory #SRPCOLOR {
        Responsibility:
        Manage command history navigation
        --
        + add(command: String)
        + previous(): Option<String>
        + next(): Option<String>
    }

    class TerminalState {
        Responsibility:
        Coordinate buffer interactions
        --
        + output: OutputBuffer
        + input: InputBuffer
        + history: CommandHistory
    }

    class CommandOrchestrator #SRPCOLOR {
        Responsibility:
        Orchestrate command execution workflow
        --
        + handle_command(...)
    }

    class NaturalLanguageOrchestrator #SRPCOLOR {
        Responsibility:
        Orchestrate LLM query workflow
        --
        + handle_query(...)
    }

    TerminalState *-- OutputBuffer
    TerminalState *-- InputBuffer
    TerminalState *-- CommandHistory

    note right of OutputBuffer
        **Buffer Components SRP**:
        Each buffer has ONE responsibility:
        - OutputBuffer: Only handles output display
        - InputBuffer: Only handles text input
        - CommandHistory: Only handles history

        **Benefits**:
        - Can test each independently
        - Changes to scrolling don't affect input
        - Easy to add features to one buffer
        - Reusable in other contexts
    end note

    note right of CommandOrchestrator
        **Orchestrators SRP**:
        Each orchestrator has ONE workflow:
        - CommandOrchestrator: Only command execution
        - NaturalLanguageOrchestrator: Only LLM queries
        - TabCompletionHandler: Only tab completion

        **Benefits**:
        - main.rs stays clean and focused
        - Each workflow can be tested independently
        - Easy to add new workflows
        - Clear separation of concerns
    end note
}

' 5. Dependency Injection / Composition Over Inheritance
package "5. Dependency Injection & Composition" {
    note as DI_OVERVIEW
        **Pattern**: Dependency Injection
        **Purpose**: Decouple components, enable testing
        **Benefits**: Easy to mock dependencies, flexible configurations
        **Implementation**: Pass dependencies as constructor arguments
    end note

    class CommandExecutor {
        - No dependencies stored
        - Stateless utility class
    }

    class NaturalLanguageOrchestrator {
        - llm_client: Arc<dyn LLMClientTrait>
        - renderer: ResponseRenderer
        --
        + new(llm_client, renderer): Self
    }

    interface LLMClientTrait {
        + query(text: &str): Result<String>
    }

    class MockLLMClient implements LLMClientTrait
    class HttpLLMClient implements LLMClientTrait

    NaturalLanguageOrchestrator --> LLMClientTrait
    LLMClientTrait <|-- MockLLMClient
    LLMClientTrait <|-- HttpLLMClient

    note right of NaturalLanguageOrchestrator
        **Dependency Injection Benefits**:

        **Testing**:
        ```rust
        let mock_client = Arc::new(MockLLMClient::new());
        let orchestrator = NaturalLanguageOrchestrator::new(
            mock_client, renderer
        );
        ```

        **Production**:
        ```rust
        let http_client = Arc::new(HttpLLMClient::new(url));
        let orchestrator = NaturalLanguageOrchestrator::new(
            http_client, renderer
        );
        ```

        **No code changes needed** - only dependency swap!
    end note
}

' 6. Lazy Initialization / Singleton Pattern
package "6. Lazy Initialization & Singleton" {
    note as LAZY_OVERVIEW
        **Pattern**: Lazy Singleton
        **Purpose**: Initialize expensive resources once, reuse globally
        **Benefits**: Zero-cost abstraction, thread-safe, performance optimized
        **Implementation**: once_cell::Lazy + static
    end note

    class CompiledPatterns #PATTERNCOLOR {
        - command_syntax: RegexSet
        - natural_language: RegexSet
        - shell_operators: RegexSet
        - question_words: RegexSet
        - articles: RegexSet
    }

    class CommandCache #PATTERNCOLOR {
        - available: HashSet<String>
        - unavailable: HashSet<String>
        - aliases: HashMap<String, String>
    }

    note right of CompiledPatterns
        **Lazy Singleton Pattern**:
        ```rust
        static PATTERNS: Lazy<CompiledPatterns> = Lazy::new(|| {
            CompiledPatterns {
                command_syntax: RegexSet::new([...]),
                // ... compile all patterns
            }
        });
        ```

        **Benefits**:
        - Patterns compiled once at startup
        - Reused for all classifications
        - 10-100x faster than runtime compilation
        - Thread-safe via once_cell
        - Zero overhead after first access
    end note

    note right of CommandCache
        **Thread-Safe Singleton Cache**:
        ```rust
        static COMMAND_CACHE: Lazy<RwLock<CommandCache>> =
            Lazy::new(|| RwLock::new(CommandCache::new()));
        ```

        **Performance**:
        - 99% read workload → RwLock optimal choice
        - Cache hits: <1μs
        - Cache misses: 1-5ms (expensive PATH lookup)
        - Poisoning recovery: into_inner() pattern
    end note
}

' Summary Grid
note bottom
    **Design Patterns Summary**:

    1. **Chain of Responsibility** (Input Classification)
       - 9 handlers in strict order
       - Fast paths first for performance
       - Flexible, easy to add handlers

    2. **Strategy Pattern** (Package Managers)
       - 7 package manager implementations
       - Runtime selection by priority
       - Cross-platform support

    3. **Builder Pattern** (Terminal Construction)
       - Flexible, testable construction
       - Dependency injection
       - Sensible defaults

    4. **Single Responsibility Principle** (Buffers & Orchestrators)
       - Each component has one reason to change
       - Easy testing and maintenance
       - Improved reusability

    5. **Dependency Injection** (LLM Client)
       - Mock for testing, real for production
       - No code changes needed
       - Flexible configurations

    6. **Lazy Singleton** (Patterns & Cache)
       - Zero-cost initialization
       - Thread-safe global state
       - Performance optimized
end note

@enduml
